{
  "text": "Maternal nutritional status has been associated with variation in male-tofemale ratio. Animal studies suggest that offspring sex ratio varies in response to environmental conditions associated with nutritional stress [CITATION_1] . In red deer hinds in the Isle of Rhum, for example, the proportion of males born declined each year with increasing population density and with winter rainfall [CITATION_2] . Similar results were reported in the Fallow deer, where a lower sex ratio was found in deer having low energy diet [CITATION_3] . Similar examples exist in birds, where females bird in better condition produce more male offspring [CITATION_4] , and an excess of females are produced when mothers are in poor condition [CITATION_5] ) selective survival of females under conditions of maternal nutritional stress.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "7463888",
